ckson’s murder marked the transition from Black Power to the prison abolition movement in ways that highlighted the relationship between surveillance, policing, incarceration, and anti-Black violence. By foregrounding the photographed, collaged, filmed, and drawn Black body, Aranke demonstrates that corporeality and corpses are crucial to the efforts to shape visions of a Black future free from white supremacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aAfrican American artxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican Americans in art. 0aBlack Arts movementzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlack powerzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical artzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics in art. 0aSocial problems in art. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023937?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023937423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023937/original  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles